snippet.title: TWO YEARS IN PARIS - Lime Scootin' & Wheely Poppin Around - Maison Maison Is The First in the Game!
snippet.description:
Maison Maison makes their entry as the first official Waypoint in the game, and I forget that I've been back in Paris for two years for way too much of the video. Help me make better videos at http://patreon.com/jayswanson and then find me on the internet in all of the usual spots:

Grab my guide to Paris here: http://bit.ly/ParisVloggersGuide

More swag here:
http://bit.ly/ShirtOfTheMonth (shirts and hat)
http://bit.ly/JaysGearList (my gear and books)
https://gum.co/camerafour (Disposable Camera Four digital scans)

Follow me here:
http://twitter.com/jayonaboat
http://instagram.com/jayswanson

Music by: DJ Quads

My name is Jay Swanson - I'm an American writer living in Paris on an artist visa and hoping to make the city of light my home base - at least for the foreseeable future. I write science-fiction and fantasy, vlog daily, and love pizza a little too much.

Links below to Amazon are affiliate links - meaning if you click through them and buy something, I'll get some pennies. Thanks! (The FTC wants me to tell you that up front)

FAQ:
How long have you lived in France? On and off for over two years.

What do you miss most about ho- NACHOS

You're always talking about living on some ship. WHAT SHIP? - I made a "Draw My Life" video that explains a lot here: https://youtu.be/-MrvL37jTKM

Where are you from originally? - Pullman, Washington - a small university/agricultural town near Idaho (and yes, the potatoes are amazing).

What do you film with? - I've made a lot of changes recently, but I try to keep my gear list up to date if you want to see what I use and buy some for yourself: http://bit.ly/JaysGearList

What do you edit with? - Adobe Premiere - it's pretty much all I've ever used since high school.

Aren't you ever freaked out by leaving your camera behind to film yourself? - Yep. But not too badly - I tend to be careful when I do.

Why are you living in #Paris? - Because I've always wanted to; I feel at home here: https://youtu.be/4Vivf6MqMxQ

Do you speak French? Oui. https://youtu.be/va1QjaHgij8

You talk a lot about the books you're working on, what are they about? - They're sci-fi (and fantasy) and I've got a decent pitch for you here: https://youtu.be/W2bKt4_Tp4E

Do you make money off YouTube? - Ha, no. I wish. It took me over 500 videos to make my first total $100 off adsense. I think it will slowly change, but VERY slowly.

I really enjoy your videos, how can I support you? - The easiest and best way to support me is through Patreon, where you can pitch in as little as $1/mo to help me make better videos: http://patreon.com/jayswanson

I don't trust this Patreon thing - can I just paypal you? - Here's my ko-fi if that's your thing (and coffee is your game): https://ko-fi.com/jayswanson

But I want to send you something tangible! - I do have a wishlist on Amazon, though it's a bit complicated with the international shipping situation. This is the US one: http://amzn.to/2ykS9Ux

And here's the French wishlist: http://bit.ly/JaysFrenchWishList

Thanks for watching!

replies.textDisplay: Hi Yvonne,if you see this I recommend "Long Ago and Far Away" by W.H Hudson. I found it spellbinding when I read it a few years ago. It's about his growing up on a farm on the Argentina pampas. In later life he lived in England and mooched about the Berkshire and Wiltshire Downs and wrote about nature. I really enjoyed reading his description of the festivities at Stonehenge  on midsummer day in 1907 showing that partying at the stones has got a long heritage!

replies.textDisplay:
+Jay Swanson Jay, just some other information on how Dutch infrastructure works. I'll give an example of why the 60cm threshold is so important. Normally, if there is a one-way street those have a counter-flow possible for bikes. Amsterdam is littered with them. It is a painted white line. What that tells the motorists to stay behind the bike already on the other side of road to protect the counter-flow lane.
In Rotterdam there are few wider roads where there one-way roads equipped with genuine bikepaths on both sides ranging in width from 45cm to 60cm. Since the width of the car lane is at least 3m when there is no heavy traffic ie anything transporting goods, those once bidirectional make nice parking lanes. Those were redesigned not too long, the parking lane was widened by 15cm, bikepaths stayed the same, car lane width decreasing to 2.7m. The reason for it was to reduce the average speed (measured over time ie actual average speed) from 23km to 20km. Little things like that do matter in inner cities. Those not living in the Netherlands wouldn't understand stuff like that but it is exactly that attention to detail which makes cycling here somewhat pleasant. Ah well. 😉

replies.textDisplay:
Dayglo orange and maybe some reflective tape at the back?

Just kidding of course, though with some serious undertones. Even in the UK it is advisable to bike WITHOUT a helmet. Reason for it are motorists have a tendency to pass closer by when wearing a helmet. Same thing happens on bikes, scooters and wheels. There were studies done in Canada, UK, Australia, Germany, Denmark, Norway, Swedish and the Netherlands and all of them showed the outcome plus or minus 2%. Motorists pass by normally at 60cm from a bike, when wearing a helmet it drops down to 45cm. 15cm mignt sound peanuts but on a bike it is the difference between comfortable cycling and not bothering to cycle again.
